Quod te absente, &c- “ Whate’er your son has in your absence committed, is null and void in law and equity.” -11, Restitui in integrum. A phrase used by lawyers, signifying “to be restored to its pristine state :’' and it was applied not only to things but also to persons. — 12. Et id impetrabis. As sar as the son was concerned, the cause had been decided‚ and Judgment given against him. But then this happened in the absence of the father. Demipho might, therefore, commence a new suit in his own person, with every hope of success. In certain cases, especially when any mistake or fraud had been committed, the praetor reversed the sentence of the judges, in which case he was said damnatos integrum restituere, or judicia restituere. Comp. Cic. Verr. v. 6.
